issue.title: Detect xdebug.use_compression and set correct extension
issue.body:
Xdebug 3.1 enables compression of the cachegrind files automatically so the extension of the output by default is not .cachegrind but .cachegrind.gz.

This patch adds a check to see if compression is enabled and then uses .cachegrind.gz instead of .cachegrind as extension.

issue.title: Executing "older" migrations
issue.body: If there exists a migration, that has not been executed yet, with a timestamp older than the last executed migration in the project, that migration will show with status `n/a` when executing `bin/console phpcr:migrations:status`, but running `bin/console phpcr:migrations:migrate` will never execute that migration. You would have to downgrade all newer migrations, then upgrade that specific migration and finally upgrade all newer migrations again. This usually happens, when you upgrade a bundle which has new migrations. Doctrine-Migrations handles this by just executing all the non-executed migrations in the order of their timestamp, no matter if there are newer migrations that have already been executed.

comment.body: I guess it would be fine to copy the behavior of the Doctrine bundle here, but also sounds like a potential issue. Surely if that migration were executed it could break all subsequent migrations? Could the solution rather be to delete it and create a new migration?

issue.title: Executing "older" migrations
issue.body: If there exists a migration, that has not been executed yet, with a timestamp older than the last executed migration in the project, that migration will show with status `n/a` when executing `bin/console phpcr:migrations:status`, but running `bin/console phpcr:migrations:migrate` will never execute that migration. You would have to downgrade all newer migrations, then upgrade that specific migration and finally upgrade all newer migrations again. This usually happens, when you upgrade a bundle which has new migrations. Doctrine-Migrations handles this by just executing all the non-executed migrations in the order of their timestamp, no matter if there are newer migrations that have already been executed.

issue.title: Executing "older" migrations
issue.body: If there exists a migration, that has not been executed yet, with a timestamp older than the last executed migration in the project, that migration will show with status `n/a` when executing `bin/console phpcr:migrations:status`, but running `bin/console phpcr:migrations:migrate` will never execute that migration. You would have to downgrade all newer migrations, then upgrade that specific migration and finally upgrade all newer migrations again. This usually happens, when you upgrade a bundle which has new migrations. Doctrine-Migrations handles this by just executing all the non-executed migrations in the order of their timestamp, no matter if there are newer migrations that have already been executed.

pull_request.body:
Xdebug 3.1 enables compression of the cachegrind files automatically so the extension of the output by default is not .cachegrind but .cachegrind.gz.

This patch adds a check to see if compression is enabled and then uses .cachegrind.gz instead of .cachegrind as extension.

comment.body:
What problem are we trying to solve - replacing an old command with a new one isn't solving a problem in itself. As said I find this useful primarily for expanding FQNs in XML and YAML (but also Markdown) and it doesn't really map to LSP as a code action as every single word would be eligible for expansion, and for PHP we have already established that it would bring little value. It would only be possible in it's current form as a custom Command which would then require a client-side addition (e.g. in the vscode client or as nvim configuration).

So short of opening a can of worms I would close this I think.
